## BrowseCentral labels (Cursor rule)

Use these rules to write browseCentral labels that match the Scalekit developer documentation style. Apply them to all browseCentral frontmatter labels.

### Label style principles
- **Maximum 3-5 words** - Keep concise but add context when needed
- **Action-oriented** - Start with verbs when possible
- **Specific and clear** - Add context when simple labels are ambiguous
- **Outcome-focused** - Describe what users accomplish and the context

### Writing patterns
- **Action + Object**: "Invite users", "Restrict sign-up", "Set up SCIM"
- **Feature name**: "Enterprise SSO", "Passwordless quickstart"
- **Task completion**: "Run migrations", "Migrate auth", "Merge identities"
- **Specific context**: "Configure Scalekit MCP server", "Validate incoming API requests"
- **Integration context**: "Build MCP auth with your existing auth system"

### Words to avoid
- **Instructional prefixes**: "How to", "Guide to", "Implement", "Configure", "Learn", "Understand"
- **Verbose phrases**: "Step-by-step guide", "Complete tutorial", "Detailed documentation"
- **Weak verbs**: "Enable", "Allow", "Provide", "Support"

### Good examples
```yaml
browseCentral:
  label: "Run migrations"        # Not: "Migration guide"
  label: "Onboard customers"    # Not: "How to onboard enterprise customers"
  label: "Lookup terminology"   # Not: "Reference glossary"
  label: "Get help"             # Not: "Contact us for support"
  label: "Migrate auth"         # Not: "Authentication migration guide"
```

### More good examples
- "Configure Scalekit MCP server" (not "Configure MCP")
- "Validate incoming API requests" (not "Validate Tokens")
- "Build MCP auth with your existing auth system" (not "Custom auth")
- "Passwordless quickstart" (not "Passwordless Headless API quickstart")
- "Set up SCIM" (not "Configure SCIM provisioning")
- "Cognito integration" (not "AWS Cognito integration with Scalekit SSO")

### Label testing checklist
- [ ] Maximum 3-5 words (more if context needed)
- [ ] No "How to", "Guide to", "Learn", "Understand"
- [ ] Action-oriented when possible
- [ ] Clear outcome and context
- [ ] Specific when simple labels are ambiguous
- [ ] Scannable at a glance
- [ ] Consistent with other labels